%N A387955 Total sum of major indices of heapable permutations of length n.
%C A387955 A permutation of [1..n] is heapable if it can be inserted, one element at a time, into a binary min-heap without violating the heap property.
%C A387955 The major index of a permutation p = (p1, p2, ..., pn) is the sum of the positions i (1 <= i <= n-1) where a descent occurs, that is, where pi > pi+1. Formally: maj(p) = Sum { i : pi > pi+1 }.
%C A387955 In other words, the major index is obtained by adding all indices i for which the element pi is greater than the next element pi+1.
%H A387955 Benjamin Chen, Michael Cho, Mario Tutuncu-Macias, and Tony Tzolov, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.dam.2023.01.025">Efficient methods of calculating the number of heapable permutations</a>, Discrete Applied Mathematics Volume 331, 31 May 2023, Pages 126-137.
%H A387955 Manolopoulos Panagiotis, <a href="/A387955/a387955.py.txt">Python program</a>
%e A387955 For n=4, the heapable permutations are:
%e A387955   (1,2,3,4): maj=0.
%e A387955   (1,2,4,3): descent at position 3, maj=3.
%e A387955   (1,3,2,4): descent at position 2, maj=2.
%e A387955   (1,3,4,2): descent at position 3, maj=3.
%e A387955   (1,4,2,3): descent at position 2, maj=2.
%e A387955 So the total major index across all 5 heapable permutations of length 4 is: 0+3+2+3+2=10.
